National top stories

  • 'You have a baby, you just put up with it': Hidden pain of birth trauma revealed in new survey

    When Amy Mageropoulos was pregnant with her first son Bobby, she dreamt about the time they'd spend together when he was born. But the reality of new motherhood is far from what she had imagined.

  • As a sticky Omicron wave crashes on Australia and NZ, Jacinda Ardern is trying a different approach

    New Zealanders are required to wear masks in supermarkets and shopping malls as the country battles its second wave of Omicron infections, but experts want the government to go even further.

  • US President Joe Biden tests positive for COVID

    The White House says the 79-year-old President is experiencing "very mild symptoms" and is taking Paxlovid, an antiviral drug designed to reduce the severity of the disease. 

  • Putin and Zelenskyy deny health rumours, with both blaming disinformation

    The Kremlin says claims the Russian President is unwell are the work of foreign disinformation operatives. Volodmyr Zelenskyy says similar claims about his own health are the work of Russian cyber attacks.

  • 'I didn't know this could happen to me': The glaring hole in our national conversation on domestic violence

    As women's safety ministers from across the country meet today, a key focus will be on a new, national plan to end violence against women. But there's a strong call for us to have a much more inclusive conversation about the impact of domestic violence.

  • Former carbon pricing mastermind Greg Combet backs proposed fix for Australia's energy crisis

    Former federal climate change minister backs proposed fix for crisis-riddled national electricity market, calling for ideology to be taken out of debate.

  • Australia facing nursing shortage as more than two years of COVID takes its toll

    More than two and a half years into the pandemic, nurses are needed more than ever — but many are burnt out and fatigued, and some are even leaving the industry.

  • 'Unprecedented growth in house prices': OECD calls for cap on housing tax breaks benefiting the rich

    Capping tax breaks for housing could help reduce house prices and ensure that property is not concentrated in the hands of older and wealthier Australians, the OECD says. 

  • Foot-and-mouth viral fragments in meat at Adelaide Airport and Melbourne supermarkets prompts biosecurity blitz

    Australia's chief vet says the fragments — which were found in potentially unlawful imports — were not live and posed no risk to human health.

  • 'Into the mouth of a bear': Ukrainian refugees being sent to Russia, their passports confiscated

    Under a strategy laid out in Russian government documents, some Ukrainians are being transported to Russia's Far East, closer to Japan than Ukraine, and are being warned to tell nobody they want to return home.

  • Sara has joined a growing list of students derailed by substandard TAFE courses

    More online courses from troubled educator Chisholm TAFE have been found to be non-compliant.

  • 'Can't buy it, so let's create it': More than a decade ago, Alex had a dream about a 'better' way of living in a capital city

    Co-housing is still unconventional in Australia, but the number of projects is on the rise. Residents say housing models like this reduce the cost of living and foster community.

  • Could floating cardboard box homes be the newest housing solution?

    The Netherlands has short-term, modular accommodation — made out of cardboard segments that weigh 500 kilograms each — and you can stay in them from $370 a night. 

  • Why this FIFA legend knows the World Cup will change the game for women's football in Australia

    Winning a World Cup at home can change the game for women's football  — something FIFA legend Carla Overbeck knows firsthand. 

  • Here's what some experts think China's economic woes could mean for Australians

    From a banking crisis to property market slumps, China's economy is under stress and the country also recently recorded its lowest quarterly growth rate figure since 1990. What might those challenges mean for Australians?
  • analysis

    Climate bill front and centre when parliament starts but it’s the least of Albanese’s problems

    If you're outside staring in, you'd probably say the Albanese government is looking good. If you're inside gazing out, you'd likely think its challenges appear little short of dire, writes Michelle Grattan.

  • Solicitor shortage in regional NSW forces some to represent themselves in court

    There are calls for legal training to be made more accessible for those who want to stay in the bush as shrinking numbers of solicitors working in regional NSW means some people have to drive hours to find legal help.

  • BBC to pay 'substantial damages' to former royal nanny over Diana interview

    The BBC agrees to pay "substantial damages" to the former nanny of Britain's Prince William and Prince Harry over the broadcaster's much-criticised 1995 interview with the late Princess Diana.

  • I joined the CWA expecting craft help. Instead, I discovered a century-old women's rights lobby group

    Throughout its 100-year history, the Country Women's Association has advocated for women's issues at all levels of government — and won many battles. 

  • Does seafood need to come from the coast? This entrepreneur doesn't think so

    Martin Zhang is out to prove he can farm prawns anywhere in the world, starting with inland country Queensland.

  • US probes Huawei over Chinese telecom giant's possible capture of American military information

    The US government is investigating Huawei over concerns US mobile phone towers fitted with its gear could capture sensitive information from military bases and missile silos that the company could then transmit to China, according to sources.

  • As more species face extinction, crocodiles are thriving and 'moving south'

    As Australian ecosystems continue to deteriorate, saltwater crocodiles in the Northern Territory are growing in population, according to a national outlook. 

  • Gas giant Inpex commits to a net zero emissions future in the Northern Territory. Will it get there?

    An energy expert says it's "ambitious" to think a net zero agreement between gas giant Inpex and the Northern Territory government will be enough to offset carbon emissions from the company's expanding projects. 

  • 'China won't let up': Beijing ramps up campaign against AUKUS nuclear submarine deal

    A new report out of Beijing declares the AUKUS nuclear submarine project is a grave risk to non-proliferation and warns that Australia may be intent on developing nuclear weapons.

  • Mother finds it's cheaper to fly interstate with kids for bulk-billing doctor than visit her local one

    It sounds bonkers, but for Tasmanian mum Bec Haight, it's cheaper for her to fly her family to Melbourne than to be seen by a doctor in her home city.

  • Meet the Rockets, the all-abilities Aussie rules team changing lives and a community

    For more than a decade, one Aussie rules team in regional Victoria has ensured all players are included in the experience, no matter their abilities.

  • How Aussie cyclist Tiffany Cromwell is preparing with her F1 partner for Tour de France Femmes

    Cromwell is sharing training tips with her partner, F1 star Valtteri Bottas, as she gets ready for the inaugural Tour de France Femmes.

  • Tahlia McGrath's T20 batting average skyrockets as Australia smashes Ireland

    She has only batted four times for Australia in T20s and won player of the match each time it has happened - and now Tahlia McGrath has a batting average that has to be seen to be believed. 

  • 'I'm not going to accept that this is how it ends': Māori artist says setback won't derail her musical journey

    Singer/songwriter Juran moved from the Northern Territory to Sydney to work with a manager she had landed in the Harbour City. Then that manager stopped answering her calls.

  • Italian Prime Minister Mario Draghi resigns after coalition falls apart

    Italian President Sergio Mattarella dissolves the parliament, clearing the way for an early election after Prime Minister Mario Draghi quit following the collapse of his national unity government.

  • 'Shouldn't be paying to keep coal and gas': Green energy backers attack capacity market proposal

    Renewable energy advocates are warning against locking in extra payments for coal and gas, saying it could derail the switch to clean power.

  • The world's oldest known male giant panda has died, at age 35

    Three weeks after An An's health started to deteriorate due to high blood pressure, the giant panda is being remembered for his "cleverness and playfulness".

  • Sam Kerr adds US award to long list of accolades

    After a stellar season, Kerr is named the best international athlete in women's football at the ESPY in the United States.

  • Opponents of $4.5bn fertiliser plant 'hopeful' as build goes on hold

    Traditional owners who have been fighting an industrial development near ancient rock art in WA's north say a pause to construction has given them hope.
